          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"week_number\":1,\"phase_type\":\"Base\",\"weekly_target_km\":40,\"is_deload_week\":false,\"sunday\":{\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"notes\":\"14 km easy long run at 5:52–6:43/km. Keep effort conversational throughout — this is aerobic foundation work, not a race. Stay in the lower half of your easy pace range if the effort feels high.\"},\"monday\":{\"slot_type\":\"Rest\",\"workout_type\":null,\"notes\":\"Full rest day after your long run. Sleep and nutrition today are part of training, not a break from it.\"},\"tuesday\":{\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"notes\":\"8 km easy run at 5:52–6:43/km. Focus on relaxed form and controlled breathing. This run builds aerobic volume without adding meaningful fatigue.\"},\"wednesday\":{\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"Tempo\",\"notes\":\"7 km total: 2 km easy warm-up, 3 km at threshold pace (4:53/km), 2 km easy cool-down. Threshold work builds your lactate clearance capacity — the foundation of half-marathon fitness.\"},\"thursday\":{\"slot_type\":\"Rest\",\"workout_type\":null,\"notes\":\"Rest or light walking only. Your body is consolidating yesterday's threshold stimulus. Protecting this recovery window pays dividends on Friday.\"},\"friday\":{\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"notes\":\"8 km easy at 5:52–6:43/km. A second easy run mid-week reinforces aerobic base without stressing the systems stressed on Wednesday.\"},\"saturday\":{\"slot_type\":\"CrossTrain\",\"workout_type\":\"CrossTrain\",\"notes\":\"30–45 min low-impact cross-training (cycling, swimming, or yoga). Keeps weekly activity rhythm without adding running load. Good time to address hip and IT band mobility given your history.\"},\"week_summary\":\"Welcome to Week 1, Lee. This opening week matches your current weekly volume of 40 km and establishes the rhythm we'll build on for the next 15 weeks. Your pace-zone index of 42.0 tells us you have a strong aerobic engine already — your 48:00 10K translates to a current half-marathon capability in the 1:47–1:49 range, meaning your 1:45:00 goal is genuinely within reach with consistent, structured work. The week is structured around three core principles: an aerobic long run on Sunday, one quality session mid-week (threshold), and easy volume to fill the aerobic cup. Saturday's cross-training slot is intentional — 5 days of running at your current load would push toward the upper edge of what's sustainable, and keeping one day as cross-train protects your IT band history while maintaining fitness. Run your easy runs *easy* — the Daniels-Gilbert zones set your easy range at 5:52–6:43/km for good physiological reason. Aerobic adaptation happens at low intensity, and running too fast on easy days is the single most common mistake at your experience level. What questions do you have before we get started?\"}"
        }
      ]
    }
